# Testing Standards

## Test Runner

- **Framework:** Vitest 3 with jsdom environment
- **Setup file:** `setupTests.ts` (root) — mocks Canvas, IndexedDB, pointer events
- **Config:** `vitest.config.mts` — defines package aliases and coverage thresholds

## Coverage Thresholds (must not drop below)

| Metric     | Minimum |
|------------|---------|
| Lines      | 60%     |
| Branches   | 70%     |
| Functions  | 63%     |
| Statements | 60%     |

Run: `yarn test:coverage --watch=false`

## Co-location Rule

Every source file `foo.ts` that contains non-trivial logic **must** have a sibling test file `foo.test.ts` in the same directory. React components use `ComponentName.test.tsx`.

Exceptions: pure type files, constant-only files, and thin re-export files.

## Test Helpers

Global test mocks are in `packages/excalidraw/tests/helpers/`:
- `mocks.ts` — `mockThrottleRAF`, canvas mocks
- `polyfills.ts` — `testPolyfills` applied globally
- `colorize.ts` — terminal color helpers for test output
- `fixtures/` — shared fixture data for element snapshots

Import these from `"./helpers/mocks"` etc., never duplicate mock logic.

## Vitest Conventions

```ts
// Use Vitest globals (no explicit import needed — globals: true in config)
describe("module name", () => {
  it("should do X when Y", () => {
    expect(result).toEqual(expected);
  });
});

// Mock with vi.fn() / vi.spyOn()
vi.spyOn(window.crypto, "getRandomValues").mockReturnValue(new Uint8Array(12));

// Avoid vi.mock() on large modules — prefer spyOn for surgical mocking
```

## Async Tests

```ts
it("handles async errors", async () => {
  await expect(riskyAsyncFn()).rejects.toThrow("expected message");
});
```

## What NOT to Test

- Visual canvas rendering (use manual browser testing)
- Firebase calls (these are integration concerns, not unit test scope)
- Exact pixel positions of rendered elements in jsdom

## Running Tests

```bash
yarn test:app --watch=false            # full run, no watch
yarn test:app --watch=false foo.test   # run a single file
yarn test:coverage --watch=false       # with coverage report
yarn test:update                       # update snapshots
```
